00:12:44,080 --> 00:12:51,040
was encountered. I looked into the chart, and it turned out that 11 or 12 years earlier,

117
00:12:51,040 --> 00:12:58,000
that patient had been seen at the West Roxbury VA Hospital. He had had a gastric cancer,

118
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:06,160
a stomach cancer. He had undergone a laparotomy, and I looked at the surgeon's note, saying that

119
00:13:06,160 --> 00:13:10,800
he opened the belly. He saw a tumor that was encompassing about three-quarters of the stomach.

120
00:13:10,800 --> 00:13:16,080
There were multiple liver metastases, deposits that were biopsied, shown to be the gastric cancer

121
00:13:16,080 --> 00:13:21,440
that had spread, multiple enlarged, hardened nodes. And he took out part of the stomach,

122
00:13:21,440 --> 00:13:28,160
I guess, as a palliative measure, left the rest of the disease in place, and the patient recovered,

123
00:13:28,160 --> 00:13:32,640
and about a week later went home. Well, as I turned the page of the chart, the patient comes

124
00:13:32,640 --> 00:13:38,640
back three months later. Nobody had expected to see him. And he was doing fine. He was gaining

125
00:13:38,640 --> 00:13:45,120
weight. Six months later, he was back working. And here he was 12 years later, having lived the

126
00:13:45,120 --> 00:13:52,240
past 10 or 11 years completely normally. And so I took part in removing his gallbladder under

127
00:13:52,240 --> 00:13:58,640
supervision, of course. And his belly was completely clean of cancer. There was no evidence of cancer

128
00:13:58,640 --> 00:14:04,080
of any kind. And we went back and looked at his, be sure it was the same patient, re-reviewed the

129
00:14:04,080 --> 00:14:11,440
pathology. Sure enough, it was a cancer that had spontaneously disappeared over time in the absence

130
00:14:11,440 --> 00:14:18,480
of any therapy. One of the rarest events in medicine, and that is to have the spontaneous

131
00:14:18,480 --> 00:14:27,520
regression of cancer without any treatments being given. Somehow, his body had rejected the cancer.

132
00:14:28,480 --> 00:14:33,040
And I then did what turned out, of course, to be a very naive experiment. But I was wondering

133
00:14:33,040 --> 00:14:40,320
whether or not this patient who had somehow cured his own cancer could be somehow taken advantage of

134
00:14:40,320 --> 00:14:44,800
to treat other patients. And it turned out we had another patient in the hospital with a gastric

135
00:14:44,800 --> 00:14:50,560
cancer, a veteran, who happened to have the same blood type. And so I called up the head of the

136
00:14:50,560 --> 00:14:55,520
surgery department, Brownie Wheeler, and said, hey, I want to take a blood transfusion from this

137
00:14:55,520 --> 00:15:01,760
patient who spontaneously was cured and give it to this other patient. And he said, okay, that was

138
00:15:01,760 --> 00:15:09,280
the IRB as existed at that time. And so we actually got blood from this one patient and infused it into

139
00:15:09,280 --> 00:15:14,160
the other veteran. But of course, it didn't do anything. And the other patient ended up dying of

140
00:15:14,160 --> 00:15:20,160
his gastric cancer. But at least planted the seed that, in fact, maybe there was something

141
00:15:21,120 --> 00:15:28,400
in the immune system that caused the rejection of that cancer, much as you would a foreign transplant.

142
00:15:28,960 --> 00:15:37,120
And the body's major defense mechanism, of course, against foreign invaders is the immune system.

143
00:15:37,120 --> 00:15:44,240
It got me thinking about potential immune manipulations. But there was a second patient

144
00:15:45,360 --> 00:15:50,240
that also influenced me a great deal. And that was a patient that had been seen about a year before

145
00:15:50,240 --> 00:15:55,680
I came to the Brigham as an intern. And this was a patient who had received one of the early kidney

