00:15:55,680 --> 00:16:03,520
transplants that were developed and innovated at the Brigham Hospital. He had received a kidney

147
00:16:03,520 --> 00:16:10,720
from a young individual who died in a motorcycle accident. And that kidney was transplanted into

148
00:16:10,720 --> 00:16:17,280
the recipient. And the recipient developed widespread renal cell cancer. And it turned out,

149
00:16:17,280 --> 00:16:22,400
after study, that the kidney that had been transplanted inadvertently had contained a renal

150
00:16:22,400 --> 00:16:27,440
cancer. That then, in this other patient, under the influence of immunosuppressive medications,

151
00:16:27,440 --> 00:16:37,280
had spread widely through his body. So in an attempt to control this, the immunosuppressive

152
00:16:37,280 --> 00:16:42,160
medications were stopped. Of course, the kidney rejected and had to be removed.

153
00:16:44,240 --> 00:16:50,720
But the patient's cancer then went away as well, because it, too, was allogeneic. It, too, came from

154
00:16:51,520 --> 00:17:03,120
the genome of the original donor. So what did that teach one? Well, it showed that a large,

155
00:17:03,120 --> 00:17:11,840
invasive, vascularized cancer could be caused to reject completely by the immune system. If you

156
00:17:11,840 --> 00:17:19,920
had a strong enough stimulus, that could mediate that rejection. And so it was that spontaneous

157
00:17:19,920 --> 00:17:25,200
regression. Maybe this demonstration that the immune system, more directly by removing

158
00:17:25,200 --> 00:17:34,240
immunosuppressive medications, could result in tumor collapse and regression that tended to

159
00:17:34,240 --> 00:17:38,960
put me on the path towards cancer. But I was already pretty much there because of what I had

160
00:17:38,960 --> 00:17:46,880
seen as a doctor in cancer patients. Now, in the late 1960s, what was understood about the

161
00:17:47,840 --> 00:17:52,560
human immune system as it pertained to even viruses, let alone cancer? I mean,

162
00:17:53,440 --> 00:17:57,760
had MHC class one and class two been identified yet? I don't think they were identified until the

163
00:17:57,760 --> 00:18:07,360
mid-70s, right? Class one in the 70s and the early 80s, class two. But when I started in 1974,

164
00:18:09,440 --> 00:18:15,920
the idea of immunotherapy was a dream. There were anecdotes way back to the late 80s of

165
00:18:15,920 --> 00:18:22,800
tumors going away when people got an infection, but really nothing stable. There was no ability

166
00:18:22,800 --> 00:18:27,520
to measure an immune reaction against any cancer. There was no such thing as a cancer antigen that

167
00:18:27,520 --> 00:18:34,160
had ever been found. There were no manipulations you could give that might work. So it was

168
00:18:35,920 --> 00:18:43,360
a sort of a dark period when it came to knowledge about the immune system against cancer. It's a

169
00:18:43,360 --> 00:18:52,240
little hard to understand just how frequent immunologic information developed. In the 1957

170
00:18:52,240 --> 00:18:57,920
issue of the Journal of Immunology, the word lymphocyte was not in the index. We did not

171
00:18:57,920 --> 00:19:03,120
understand what small lymphocytes did, what they were doing and circulating in the 1950s.

172
00:19:04,480 --> 00:19:10,080
And so that information only came to pass in the early 60s when it was clear that

173
00:19:11,040 --> 00:19:16,560
you could transfer immunity by transferring lymphocytes in a way that you could not do by

174
00:19:16,560 --> 00:19:24,880
transferring blood or serum. And even in experimental animals, there was no manipulation

175
00:19:24,880 --> 00:19:31,600
that could cause an existing cancer to disappear. You could immunize a mouse against a tumor by

176
00:19:31,600 --> 00:19:37,760
letting it grow and then removing it and cause that mouse to resist an implantation of the same

177
00:19:37,760 --> 00:19:42,800
tumor again. But once the tumor was growing, there was no maneuver that could keep it from

178
00:19:42,800 --> 00:19:49,360
growing, no immunologic maneuver that could keep it from growing. So the field was desperately in

179
00:19:49,360 --> 00:19:58,080
need of more information. So before we get to how you arrived at the NCI, well, actually let's talk

180
00:19:58,080 --> 00:20:04,000
about that. It's a very unusual first job. How did it come about and what did you assume you would do

