195
00:21:43,440 --> 00:21:50,640
and so on. But in the course of that, I heard from one of the division directors here at the NIH,

196
00:21:51,280 --> 00:21:57,600
who I had gotten to know when I was a fellow, who came to the Brigham to interview me.

197
00:21:57,600 --> 00:22:02,800
He was wondering whether I would be interested in the position. And so he interviewed me, and

198
00:22:05,280 --> 00:22:11,680
I was expecting to stay at the Brigham at Harvard, but one day I got a phone call from him saying

199
00:22:11,680 --> 00:22:17,680
that the Chief of Surgery offered Ketchum was, had decided to retire, and the position was open July 1.

200
00:22:17,680 --> 00:22:23,920
Was I interested? And I knew I was, but I had a call. My wife, Alice, told her about it. She said,

201
00:22:23,920 --> 00:22:33,680
just pack, let's go, and off we went. Was Franny disappointed? Oh, it was a, it was a really shocking

202
00:22:33,680 --> 00:22:38,960
encounter that I had with him, and that I went in to tell him I decided to go to the NIH. I thought

203
00:22:38,960 --> 00:22:45,040
it was a place where I could best utilize my interests and knowledge, and he said no.

204
00:22:46,160 --> 00:22:50,880
And I said, look, I've decided to do it. He said, you have to stay here. It's too great an opportunity

205
00:22:50,880 --> 00:22:58,480
to turn down. And I said no, and he wasn't an easy guy to say no to, but I knew I wanted to

206
00:22:58,480 --> 00:23:06,160
come back to the, to the NIH. And finally, after almost an hour, I finally said, Dr. Moore, I'm

207
00:23:06,160 --> 00:23:12,320
not, I'm going down to Bethesda, Maryland. And I offered my hand, my hand to shake his hand

208
00:23:12,320 --> 00:23:18,560
as I was going to leave, and he refused to shake my hand, which was a little shocking. But he got

209
00:23:18,560 --> 00:23:25,200
over it finally. I left, and we became good friends, and he said all kinds of nice things about me when

210
00:23:25,200 --> 00:23:33,440
he needed to. So it worked out well. You see, at that point, I knew I wanted to study cancer. I had

211
00:23:33,440 --> 00:23:38,160
already made that absolute, absolute commitment, and the National Cancer Institute seemed like the

212
00:23:38,160 --> 00:23:47,280
right way to, to do it. And in some sense, it was a logical decision from me, given my childhood

213
00:23:47,280 --> 00:23:54,960
experience that got me interested in medicine and science. Cancer is such a devastating disease. It

214
00:23:54,960 --> 00:24:00,800
attacks innocent people through no fault of their own. It makes them and their families watch

215
00:24:00,800 --> 00:24:09,600
impotently as they progress and then die of cancer as a holocaust. And just seemed like the

216
00:24:09,600 --> 00:24:16,000
kind of thing I wanted to study. So it was around this time, I guess, a little bit before this time

217
00:24:16,000 --> 00:24:21,200
that Richard Nixon and that administration had declared a war on cancer. I believe it was just

218
00:24:21,200 --> 00:24:27,680
a year prior to that. How did that resonate with you? Did you view that with great optimism?

219
00:24:28,160 --> 00:24:34,080
Or did you think that it was naive that, you know, in a matter of years, cancer would be eradicated

220
00:24:34,080 --> 00:24:41,440
in the same way that man had gone to the moon? Well, I had great hopes for making, for making

221
00:24:41,440 --> 00:24:48,080
progress, perhaps naively, even at that point, not fully understanding all of the complexities.

222
00:24:48,880 --> 00:24:54,960
The National Cancer Act mainly influenced funding outside of the NIH. The NIH was already, I thought,

223
00:24:55,440 --> 00:25:03,600
well funded. Had a building that had been built in 1953, one of the largest buildings in this area,

224
00:25:04,720 --> 00:25:11,360
dedicated to doing research. It had hospital beds. And so that National Cancer Act didn't have much

225
00:25:11,360 --> 00:25:17,920
impact on the intramural NIH that I could see. But again, remember, I'm a worker bee. I became chief

226
00:25:17,920 --> 00:25:23,840
of the surgery branch and have never advanced in the hierarchy. I was where I wanted to be. Turn

227
00:25:23,840 --> 00:25:31,280
down a fair number of physicians. And so when it came to the influence of the National Cancer Act

228
00:25:31,280 --> 00:25:37,600
on the country as a whole, I really wasn't involved with that very much at all. I focused

229
00:25:37,600 --> 00:25:44,240
on the work that I wanted to do intramurally at the NIH. So how did you lay out a research agenda

230
00:25:44,240 --> 00:25:51,600
when you arrived in 1974? You're now finally able to, not only with the resources of money,

231
00:25:51,600 --> 00:25:58,800
but perhaps more importantly with the resources of time, lay out an agenda for hypotheses that

232
00:25:58,800 --> 00:26:08,800
you want to test to build effectively a program to systematically narrow down the set of questions.

233
00:26:08,800 --> 00:26:14,320
So what was the process by which you went about doing that? So when I came to the NIH,

234
00:26:15,280 --> 00:26:19,520
knowing I wanted to study cancer, I started reading everything I possibly could about

235
00:26:19,520 --> 00:26:25,520
therapeutic approaches, which at that point were simply surgery, radiation therapy, and chemotherapy,

236
00:26:26,720 --> 00:26:35,760
most used alone. And it was clear to me at that point that although incremental advances had been

237
00:26:35,760 --> 00:26:45,120
made over the years, surgery 3,000 years old, radiation therapy began immediately after

238
00:26:45,120 --> 00:26:55,920
Renkin discovered x-rays in 1895, and chemotherapy arose in biological and chemical warfare

239
00:26:55,920 --> 00:27:07,280
laboratories here at Fort Detrick in Dietrich, Maryland to attempt to develop these agents.

240
00:27:07,280 --> 00:27:16,480
And it was in laboratory accidents in 1942 when nitrogen mustard was inadvertently exposed to

241
00:27:16,480 --> 00:27:22,320
laboratory technicians and found to develop a lymphopenia throughout their body with their

242
00:27:22,320 --> 00:27:27,840
lymph nodes shrinking down that led a Yale physician to attempt to use nitrogen mustard,

243
00:27:29,120 --> 00:27:35,040
now known as melphalan, as a chemotherapy agent. And that was the birth of chemotherapy

244
00:27:35,040 --> 00:27:40,880
in 1942, and that started chemicals to treat, search for chemicals to treat cancer.

245
00:27:42,080 --> 00:27:48,720
But the advances that were being made were slowly and tiny incremental. I wanted something that big

246
00:27:48,720 --> 00:27:52,560
that would make a big difference. And as I began to read about the immune system,

247
00:27:54,160 --> 00:27:58,480
how little was known about it, but with the examples that I had, the intuition that I had

248
00:27:58,480 --> 00:28:04,480
developed, which is so important in science, that this might be something valuable that I decided

249
00:28:04,480 --> 00:28:13,120
to study immunology. I looked at everything I could read about, and it seemed to me that

250
00:28:14,080 --> 00:28:19,440
the immune cells that were then being recognized as the mediators of organ rejection were the

251
00:28:20,960 --> 00:28:29,280
agents that one needed to stimulate. And why not use an immune cell as a drug that has taken

252
00:28:29,280 --> 00:28:34,160
advantage of a patient's own immune reactions to try to treat the disease, immunotherapy. And I

253
00:28:34,160 --> 00:28:41,200
started with some unbelievably naive experiments. There was no way at that point to keep lymphocytes

254
00:28:41,200 --> 00:28:46,800
alive outside the body. We're talking about 1974. You could take them out, and they would die in a

255
00:28:46,800 --> 00:28:51,440
day or two. And you had no way to keep them alive. You could mix them with other cells,

256
00:28:51,440 --> 00:28:55,120
and they would stimulate for a few days, but then they would die after about a week.

257
00:28:56,560 --> 00:29:01,920
And yet I was desperate to try to use lymphocytes with immune reactivity to treat patients.

258
00:29:02,880 --> 00:29:12,320
And so I began implanting human tumors into the mesentery of mini pigs. A good friend of mine,

259
00:29:12,320 --> 00:29:17,840
David Sacks, here had developed a mini pig colony that was partially inbred at MHC Losai.

260
00:29:18,720 --> 00:29:25,920
And so I would embed a tumor in the mesentery of these mini pigs, wait about two weeks, operate

261
00:29:26,000 --> 00:29:33,840
and remove the inflamed lymph nodes that were draining that tumor, and gave those lymphocytes

262
00:29:35,360 --> 00:29:39,680
to six patients. That is, we take out their tumor, generate lymphocytes,

263
00:29:39,680 --> 00:29:45,440
react them against that tissue, and then harvest lymphocytes from that pig and administer them

264
00:29:46,000 --> 00:29:51,680
intravenously to patients. And of course, nothing happened. But it's just a sign of how desperate I

265
00:29:51,680 --> 00:29:58,560
was at that point to have some impact to be doing something. I have over the door of my lab,

266
00:29:58,560 --> 00:30:09,840
you probably remember it, when you were in the lab, it said, it's a modification of a Louis Pasteur

267
00:30:10,720 --> 00:30:15,120
saying that said, chance favors the prepared mind. And what I added to it was,

268
00:30:15,680 --> 00:30:22,320
chance favors the prepared mind only if the mind is at work. And so I was trying things. And it was

269
00:30:22,320 --> 00:30:32,640
only with the discovery of T cell growth factor in 1976 by Morgan, Rossetti and Gallo that opened

270
00:30:32,640 --> 00:30:38,320
the door to be able to manipulate lymphocytes outside the body by putting them in a growth

271
00:30:38,320 --> 00:30:45,120
factor called interleukin-2. And that was something I began to study quite intensively

272
00:30:45,680 --> 00:30:51,600
to see if one couldn't then grow lymphocytes that had anti-tumor activity and would retain it as they

273
00:30:51,600 --> 00:30:56,800
grew. None of that was known, but those were the first experiments I was doing along those lines.

274
00:30:56,800 --> 00:31:02,800
Now, before we go further, I think it's worth making sure people understand some of the

275
00:31:02,800 --> 00:31:07,680
semantics because obviously you and I can take so much of this for granted. But

276
00:31:07,680 --> 00:31:14,480
let's start with some basics about cancer. How does one define cancer? What separates

277
00:31:14,480 --> 00:31:20,720
a cancer cell from a non-cancer cell? Well, if you look at the broadest properties,

278
00:31:20,720 --> 00:31:27,040
there are two properties that separate cancer from other cells in the body. The first is

279
00:31:27,040 --> 00:31:32,800
uncontrolled growth. Virtually all of the tissues we have, either fingernails or eyebrows or you

280
00:31:32,800 --> 00:31:37,600
name it, they'll grow to a given amount and then they'll stop. Well, cancers don't have that

281
00:31:37,600 --> 00:31:44,800
signal to stop. They'll keep growing. And the second is it's the only cell that can arise in

282
00:31:44,800 --> 00:31:52,400
one part of the body and spread and live and divide and grow in another part of the body.

283
00:31:52,960 --> 00:31:59,200
And that's not true of virtually any other kind of cell. So cells with uncontrolled growth

284
00:31:59,200 --> 00:32:05,040
that can spread and grow elsewhere are the biologic properties. Now, we can dig down layer

285
00:32:05,040 --> 00:32:11,840
by layer by layer and get to the point of, well, why does a normal cell ultimately become a cancer

286
00:32:11,840 --> 00:32:18,560
cell? And we now understand that that's due to the accumulation of mutations in DNA of these cells

287
00:32:18,560 --> 00:32:26,000
divide, which explains why it's the common organs of the body, all of which have ducts. The lining

288
00:32:26,080 --> 00:32:33,200
of those ducts are constantly turning over. And as that DNA is turning over, mistakes are made

289
00:32:33,200 --> 00:32:38,000
called mutations. And it's that accumulation of mutations that results in the cancer itself. So

290
00:32:38,640 --> 00:32:42,880
we can take it all the way from the biology of uncontrolled growth, but down to the very

291
00:32:42,880 --> 00:32:47,600
molecules that are involved. We can describe it. It doesn't mean we really understand it all,

292
00:32:47,600 --> 00:32:54,000
but we can describe it. And let's also explain to people the difference between the epithelial

293
00:32:54,000 --> 00:33:02,320
tumors, the hematologic tumors, and even let's frame it as it was in 1974 in terms of what was

294
00:33:02,320 --> 00:33:09,920
a person's odds of surviving. So maybe tell folks what the common epithelial tumors are and explain

295
00:33:09,920 --> 00:33:15,280
a little bit about the, we're not going to go into staging in great detail, but what's the difference

296
00:33:15,280 --> 00:33:20,960
between local tumor versus metastatic tumor and what's the impact that has on a person's survival

297
00:33:20,960 --> 00:33:27,120
at the time you arrived at NCI? So the hematologic cancers, of course, are the blood cancers and they

298
00:33:27,120 --> 00:33:34,640
start from progenitors in the hematopoietic system, because after all, the hematopoietic system starts

299
00:33:34,640 --> 00:33:41,600
from an individual stem cell that then divides into multiple different characteristics, much as

300
00:33:41,600 --> 00:33:49,840
we all grow from a single fertilized egg from one cell that makes us what we are.

301
00:33:51,520 --> 00:34:01,440
So even back then, and a little more so now, if you developed a cancer of the bloodstream,

302
00:34:03,520 --> 00:34:08,720
which were about 10% of all cancer deaths are due to those, 90% of cancer deaths are due to

303
00:34:08,720 --> 00:34:16,000
the epithelial cancer. So these start in the solid organs of the body, and that goes all the way from

304
00:34:16,000 --> 00:34:22,560
the rectum up through the GI tract, through the stomach, through the esophagus, the pancreas,

305
00:34:22,560 --> 00:34:28,880
the GU organs, the testis, the ovary, the prostate. All of these solid organs have ducts,

306
00:34:29,920 --> 00:34:33,920
and as I've mentioned, it's the epithelial lining of the ducts that are turning over that

307
00:34:33,920 --> 00:34:40,800
become the cancer. In blood cancers, it's the more primordial cells that develop into neutrophils and

308
00:34:40,800 --> 00:34:47,360
lymphocytes and other types of cells. So let's talk about the solid tumors, which are 90% of all

309
00:34:47,360 --> 00:34:53,360
cancer deaths. Last year in the United States, there were about 600,000 deaths due to cancer,

310
00:34:53,360 --> 00:35:04,960
550,000 were due to the solid epithelial cancers. If you operate on a patient who develops a cancer

311
00:35:04,960 --> 00:35:11,040
to remove that cancer, then well over half the time that patient will be cured. That is, go on

312
00:35:11,040 --> 00:35:18,000
and live their normal lifespan. But the half, a little less than half of patients that cannot

313
00:35:18,000 --> 00:35:25,120
be cured result in this enormous tragedy of 600,000 innocent people dying of cancer every year.

314
00:35:26,320 --> 00:35:31,680
Once the cancer spreads, however, and this in my view is a dirty little secret of oncology,

315
00:35:31,840 --> 00:35:41,680
and that is that if a cancer spreads from its local site and cannot be surgically removed,

316
00:35:43,440 --> 00:35:50,800
then the death rate in that patient is 100%. That is, we have virtually no

317
00:35:52,240 --> 00:35:57,680
treatments that can cure, systemic treatments that can cure a patient with a metastatic solid

318
00:35:57,680 --> 00:36:04,320
cancer that is one that has spread to a different site that can't be surgically resected. Now,

319
00:36:04,320 --> 00:36:10,000
there are a couple of exceptions to that. There are two solid tumor exceptions that have existed

320
00:36:10,000 --> 00:36:15,840
for several decades. One is choriocarcinoma. These are cancers that start in the placenta of pregnant

321
00:36:15,840 --> 00:36:21,840
women that then spread, and you can have 90% of the lung replaced by that tumor, receive methotrexate,

322
00:36:21,920 --> 00:36:28,640
a chemotherapy drug, and it will all disappear. Still don't understand exactly how. Germ cell

323
00:36:28,640 --> 00:36:36,320
tumors in the male, tumors of the testis like Lance Armstrong, who had brain mets and lung mets,

324
00:36:36,320 --> 00:36:42,800
no matter how much they've spread, if you give patients platinum-derived chemotherapy

325
00:36:43,520 --> 00:36:48,000
regimens, you can cause complete, durable regression of that metastatic disease.

326
00:36:48,480 --> 00:36:54,640
Up until 1985, those were the only cancers that could be cured. We can now add to that list,

327
00:36:54,640 --> 00:37:00,160
solid cancers. We can now add to that list melanoma and renal cancer because Interleukin-2

328
00:37:00,800 --> 00:37:05,360
administered the patients back in the mid-80s cause complete regressions of widely metastatic

329
00:37:05,360 --> 00:37:10,480
cancer in patients that are still alive today. But that's it. Choriocarcinoma,

330
00:37:10,800 --> 00:37:16,880
germ cell tumors, melanoma, renal cancer, other than those for everyone who develops

331
00:37:17,440 --> 00:37:23,440
a spread cancer will die of it despite all the best treatments that we have. We read in the paper

332
00:37:23,440 --> 00:37:28,080
that this celebrity has cancer and they're going to fight it and they're going to beat it, but

333
00:37:28,080 --> 00:37:34,080
nobody beats it. We're in such desperate need of better treatments for patients with metastatic

334
00:37:34,560 --> 00:37:41,360
cancers because we just, we can beat them back a little bit. We can improve survival by months

335
00:37:42,240 --> 00:37:47,440
and for some cancers, maybe a few years like breast cancer and colon cancer, but everybody

336
00:37:47,440 --> 00:37:51,840
ultimately will succumb to the disease. Well, and that's what I was actually going to ask you about,

337
00:37:51,840 --> 00:37:58,240
which is if you think about the past 50 years in cancer and what you just said, I really,

338
00:37:58,240 --> 00:38:02,240
I still starkly remember having those discussions as a medical student with you.

339
00:38:03,120 --> 00:38:09,840
And the main point was we've basically just extended median survival of metastatic cancer,

340
00:38:09,840 --> 00:38:17,680
but we haven't increased overall survival. And what would be the extent to which even median

341
00:38:17,680 --> 00:38:24,240
survival has changed if we are just talking about stage four of the common cancers, breast,

342
00:38:24,240 --> 00:38:30,800
colorectal, lung, pancreatic? How much has the needle been moved with respect to median

343
00:38:31,760 --> 00:38:35,520
survival, notwithstanding the fact that overall survival hasn't changed?

344
00:38:36,880 --> 00:38:43,600
Well, if you look at current papers and advertisements, most regimens that

345
00:38:43,600 --> 00:38:47,840
ultimately get approved by the Food and Drug Administration prolong survival by

346
00:38:49,440 --> 00:38:56,800
months. Probably the best example in modern oncology is treatment of metastatic colorectal

347
00:38:56,960 --> 00:39:03,600
cancer. When I started median survival would have been maybe eight to 10 months. Now it's

348
00:39:03,600 --> 00:39:08,400
two and a half years. So there's an example where life has been extended by years. Breast

349
00:39:08,400 --> 00:39:15,040
cancer patients can go from one regimen to another, each one causing some temporary

350
00:39:16,640 --> 00:39:21,680
regression of the cancer or limitation of its growth, but the cancer will ultimately grow and

351
00:39:21,680 --> 00:39:26,560
the patient will have to move on to something else. And that's why cancer care is so remarkably

352
00:39:26,640 --> 00:39:33,760
expensive because people just move from one treatment that can prolong life by a few weeks,

353
00:39:33,760 --> 00:39:39,040
like a lot live in pancreatic cancer, six week improvement in survival. For $40,000, right?

354
00:39:40,400 --> 00:39:49,280
For enormous toxicity and huge, huge life altering expense. The most frequently prescribed drug in

355
00:39:49,280 --> 00:39:56,400
oncology today is a vastin, Bevacizumab, which can impact on blood vessels and tumors.

356
00:39:57,040 --> 00:40:04,160
And the trials of that regimen in combination with others will prolong survival in patients

357
00:40:04,160 --> 00:40:10,720
with colorectal cancer by about four and a half months. But those are the tiny increments,

358
00:40:11,280 --> 00:40:16,720
which can provide substantial, some can provide substantial benefit to patients, but

359
00:40:17,440 --> 00:40:23,280
not a curative and people are always living under the cloud of that cancer that is going to,

360
00:40:23,920 --> 00:40:32,720
is going to regrow. So we need something more dramatic than the application of surgery,

361
00:40:32,720 --> 00:40:37,840
radiation and chemotherapy barring some enormous advances in those fields.

362
00:40:37,840 --> 00:40:41,920
And I think one other point worth making for folks with respect to chemotherapy,

363
00:40:41,920 --> 00:40:45,440
I was actually just on the phone yesterday with one of my patients whose

364
00:40:45,840 --> 00:40:55,760
wife is currently recovering from surgery, from a cancer. And he asked a question about the

365
00:40:55,760 --> 00:41:00,560
efficacy of chemotherapy and how good is chemotherapy at killing cancer cells,

366
00:41:00,560 --> 00:41:05,760
which I thought was an interesting question. And it led to a discussion where I said,

367
00:41:05,760 --> 00:41:11,040
you know, the challenge with chemotherapy is not finding chemotherapeutic agents that can kill

368
00:41:11,040 --> 00:41:16,720
cancer cells. You know, I made a point that he probably had 20 chemicals in his home and in his

369
00:41:16,720 --> 00:41:23,040
garage that could kill every cancer cell remaining in his wife. The issue is how can you do that

370
00:41:23,040 --> 00:41:29,280
selectively? How could you do that and not at the same time kill the normal cells? And I think

371
00:41:29,280 --> 00:41:34,160
therein lies the arbitrage that needs to be exploited with chemotherapy and ultimately

372
00:41:34,160 --> 00:41:38,720
what we're going to talk about, which is immunotherapy. But I think that's an important

373
00:41:38,720 --> 00:41:43,600
point that many people don't understand, which is how difficult it is to thread the needle of

374
00:41:43,600 --> 00:41:48,320
chemotherapy. It's not the killing of cancer that's hard. It's the killing of cancer and not

375
00:41:48,320 --> 00:41:56,160
killing the non-cancer. No, the point you make is incredibly important because it's the selective

376
00:41:56,160 --> 00:42:02,640
killing of cancer without killing normal cells, which is not the case for virtually any chemotherapy

377
00:42:02,640 --> 00:42:08,560
or radiation therapy. Even in surgery, you have to remove some normal tissue. And so it's that

378
00:42:08,560 --> 00:42:16,320
selectivity against the cancer that's so important. And in fact, that's almost the perfect

379
00:42:16,320 --> 00:42:22,800
explanation for another reason that I think immunotherapy has potential importance because

380
00:42:22,800 --> 00:42:30,880
of its immense selectivity and sensitivity of recognition. Can recognize single amino acid

381
00:42:30,880 --> 00:42:37,200
changes in a protein and develop an immune response against it. Trivial differences that

382
00:42:37,280 --> 00:42:44,480
can distinguish normal from tumor or if you get a viral infection, destroy the virus

383
00:42:44,480 --> 00:42:49,840
in the respiratory system without destroying the respiratory epithelium. It's the exquisite

384
00:42:49,840 --> 00:42:56,800
sensitivity and specificity of the immune reaction that I think makes it such a seductively

385
00:42:56,800 --> 00:43:03,120
interesting approach to trying to develop new cancer treatments. Well, let's take a moment and

386
00:43:03,120 --> 00:43:09,200
have people get a little bit deeper on how the immune system works. I remember for me personally

387
00:43:09,200 --> 00:43:15,200
in medical school, it was one of the most interesting sets of courses we took where the

388
00:43:15,200 --> 00:43:23,280
courses in immunology, in particular how T cells worked was fascinating. It seemed to lend itself

389
00:43:23,280 --> 00:43:31,200
to a story almost and with generals and soldiers and all of these things. So explain to people,

390
00:43:31,200 --> 00:43:36,560
let's maybe start with a virus as the example because obviously in the era of coronavirus,

